01:49:45.000 --> 01:49:47.000
that were ever invading the earth

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:52.000
with minor league baseball players.

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:53.000
They would come out of the games

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:54.000
and they'd see us,

01:49:54.000 --> 01:49:56.000
and they'd call us the N-word,

01:49:56.000 --> 01:49:59.000
spit tobacco at us,

01:49:59.000 --> 01:50:01.000
and then we could actually

01:50:01.000 --> 01:50:05.000
collect indecently.

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:07.000
So my view of the Professor athletes

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:11.000
was not positive at all.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:13.000
So when I went to the next

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:14.000
abusive game,

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:18.000
the linkers were playing.

01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:20.000
And, there's a guy that said,

01:50:20.000 --> 01:50:23.000
he played high school ball with Jim Pollard.

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:25.000
He was a big star with the linkers.

01:50:25.000 --> 01:50:27.000
And he was going to go to the locker's house.

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:32.640
And so I say, I'll wait out here.

01:50:32.640 --> 01:50:34.640
Three goes in there.

01:50:34.640 --> 01:50:38.320
And so while I was waiting, George Mackey comes out.

01:50:38.320 --> 01:50:39.520
He sees me and he walks over me.

01:50:39.520 --> 01:50:41.320
How you doing, Big fella?

01:50:41.320 --> 01:50:44.680
Well, that was a real joke.

01:50:44.680 --> 01:50:47.960
Mac was 6'10 to 80.

01:50:47.960 --> 01:50:49.960
And I was 6'700.

01:50:49.960 --> 01:50:56.960
And he says, how you doing, Big fella?

01:50:56.960 --> 01:50:58.960
He said, you play center?

01:50:58.960 --> 01:50:59.960
I said, yeah.

01:50:59.960 --> 01:51:05.600
He said, well, he showed me a couple moves that he used.

01:51:05.600 --> 01:51:09.000
And says, now listen.

01:51:09.000 --> 01:51:15.640
When you get out of college, you got to come play for the Lakers.

01:51:15.640 --> 01:51:21.960
And I couldn't even make my home room team.

01:51:21.960 --> 01:51:30.800
And college was, I had no scholarships or nothing.

01:51:30.800 --> 01:51:36.000
And so I'd be working a shipyard saving up money to go to college.

01:51:36.000 --> 01:51:40.480
I was going to pay my own way.

01:51:40.480 --> 01:51:45.600
So Mac is just, after you got a college, you got to come play for the Lakers.

01:51:45.600 --> 01:51:46.600
And that was it.

01:51:46.600 --> 01:51:51.520
He was the number one guy in basketball.

01:51:51.520 --> 01:51:54.800
And he talked so nice to me.

01:51:54.800 --> 01:51:57.400
He wasn't condescending or anything.

01:51:57.400 --> 01:52:01.920
He was talking to me like off the little ball player.

01:52:01.920 --> 01:52:07.440
Well, that's going back more than 50, 60 years or something like that.

01:52:07.440 --> 01:52:12.360
And we think race relations would have been horrible back then.

01:52:12.360 --> 01:52:15.600
And they were because you've never been rosy about it.

01:52:15.600 --> 01:52:19.480
But you're saying that even back in those periods, there are always exceptions to the rules.

01:52:19.480 --> 01:52:24.960
Well, you know, remember I tell you, his folk story is going to be in the seminary.

01:52:24.960 --> 01:52:29.080
But he was just a good person.

01:52:29.080 --> 01:52:36.840
And I tell you, one of the greatest rewards I had was after George died, he had a private

01:52:36.840 --> 01:52:40.160
ceremony for his family.

01:52:40.160 --> 01:52:43.200
And I was invited.

01:52:43.200 --> 01:52:45.280
Of course, George and I had been friends.

01:52:45.280 --> 01:52:50.440
You know, we had a thing in LA we did on TV show or something.

01:52:50.440 --> 01:52:54.920
And George says, Bill, I want you to do me a big favor.

01:52:54.920 --> 01:52:56.920
I need a big favor from you.

01:52:56.920 --> 01:52:58.720
I'll let him say if you said no.

01:52:58.720 --> 01:53:01.120
I said, what's it, George?

01:53:01.120 --> 01:53:06.760
He said, I don't want to introduce you to my son.

01:53:06.760 --> 01:53:07.760
Are you kidding?

01:53:07.760 --> 01:53:09.520
That's a favor.

01:53:09.520 --> 01:53:11.000
You know?

01:53:11.000 --> 01:53:15.080
So he introduced me to his son.

01:53:15.080 --> 01:53:21.480
And he says to his son, I want you to meet Bill Russell.

01:53:21.480 --> 01:53:26.000
The greatest son of him, he played basketball.

01:53:26.000 --> 01:53:29.960
And I said, George, people forget.

01:53:29.960 --> 01:53:34.120
You know, he won three championships in five years.

01:53:34.120 --> 01:53:37.080
He was the man in basketball.

01:53:37.080 --> 01:53:39.080
But it wasn't on television, all that.

01:53:39.080 --> 01:53:41.520
So I suppose people didn't know that.

01:53:41.520 --> 01:53:50.000
But I was so flattered that this man had been so nice to me.

01:53:50.000 --> 01:54:02.840
You know, a lot of people say very, very sensitive things to kids.

01:54:02.840 --> 01:54:07.920
And I hope that I never do that.

01:54:07.920 --> 01:54:12.360
You know?

01:54:12.360 --> 01:54:16.920
Because you can injure kids.

01:54:16.920 --> 01:54:24.560
But I have this thing that I get along.

01:54:25.560 --> 01:54:31.560
But the first thing I need about, is your second thought.

01:54:31.560 --> 01:54:38.160
Because the first one is the one that might injure kids.

01:54:38.160 --> 01:54:40.160
Yeah, are you new?

01:54:40.160 --> 01:54:41.160
Yeah.

01:54:41.160 --> 01:54:47.960
I think one of your sayings was always that you don't believe there's any such thing as

01:54:47.960 --> 01:54:49.560
other people's kids.

01:54:49.560 --> 01:54:50.560
Right.

01:54:50.560 --> 01:54:56.360
Well, I'm speaking at a school in Fort Worth, Texas.

01:54:56.360 --> 01:55:00.560
And there was a day where winding down the Vietnam War.

01:55:00.560 --> 01:55:07.000
And I said, it's still a spread of other money, killer of peasants.

01:55:07.000 --> 01:55:17.200
We should take that money and re-pair an educational system.

01:55:17.200 --> 01:55:21.120
Because we haven't paid enough attention to it.

01:55:21.120 --> 01:55:24.360
We haven't paid enough money to it.

01:55:24.360 --> 01:55:28.840
And so after the speech, you know, one guy comes and says, well, listen.

01:55:28.840 --> 01:55:32.600
Your speech is already except for one thing.

01:55:32.600 --> 01:55:38.280
What you talk about is raising my taxes.

01:55:38.280 --> 01:55:44.880
And why should I pay taxes to educate other people's kids?

01:55:44.880 --> 01:55:50.640
And I said to him, two reasons you should pay taxes.

01:55:50.640 --> 01:55:57.680
One, when you were six and you first bottled you up and said you're off to school, there

01:55:57.680 --> 01:56:00.640
was a school there for you to go to.

01:56:00.640 --> 01:56:04.440
And you're fostered that building.

01:56:04.440 --> 01:56:07.320
It was there.

01:56:07.320 --> 01:56:13.800
And second, there are no other people's kids in the other states.

01:56:13.800 --> 01:56:18.240
This next generation of Americans.

01:56:18.240 --> 01:56:28.080
And if we don't educate them, we lose all the things that we think are important.

01:56:28.080 --> 01:56:40.320
Because if we do not want to top educated societies, we will not be able to compete internationally.

01:56:40.320 --> 01:56:51.880
And so we have a choice of either building our schools or picking a war.

01:56:51.880 --> 01:56:56.320
And I don't think picking a war is the best option.

01:56:56.320 --> 01:57:01.160
We can talk a little bit about your relationship to the civil rights movement.

01:57:01.160 --> 01:57:05.160
I know because that was during your play and career.

01:57:05.160 --> 01:57:06.560
It was around for a lot of it.

01:57:06.560 --> 01:57:13.240
I know once you went to Mississippi in the summer of 1964 for Charles Evers, the brother

01:57:13.240 --> 01:57:15.920
of Medgar Evers a year after he was killed.

01:57:15.920 --> 01:57:21.360
Well, you know, I was never big on organizations.

01:57:21.360 --> 01:57:32.160
And the reason for that was if you say something as part of an organization, you can be dismissed

01:57:32.160 --> 01:57:35.760
as a mouthpiece for an organization.

01:57:35.760 --> 01:57:39.880
And so they don't have to deal with what you're saying.

01:57:39.880 --> 01:57:51.600
When Medgar Evers got shot, we had a moral service for him in Boston.

01:57:51.600 --> 01:57:55.400
At the Boston government.

01:57:55.400 --> 01:57:59.920
And I said next to Charlie Evers his brother.

01:57:59.920 --> 01:58:05.040
And so I don't know what I was thinking.

01:58:05.040 --> 01:58:09.640
Well, I told him does everything I can do.

01:58:09.640 --> 01:58:13.280
Here's my home number.

01:58:13.280 --> 01:58:15.920
He used it.

01:58:15.920 --> 01:58:19.760
So he called me.

01:58:19.760 --> 01:58:29.240
That's something says we're taking a hit.

01:58:29.240 --> 01:58:32.680
More relwized.

01:58:32.680 --> 01:58:36.640
And we're down to the lowest we've been.

01:58:36.640 --> 01:58:40.200
And so we need somebody to give us a boost.

01:58:40.200 --> 01:58:45.520
To show somebody from outside cares.

01:58:45.520 --> 01:58:51.640
Sure, I said, okay, what do you want me to do?

01:58:51.640 --> 01:58:54.720
He says, you know what would be a good idea.

01:58:54.720 --> 01:59:01.720
And in your field of expertise, why don't you do some basic medical clinics in Jackson,

01:59:01.720 --> 01:59:07.560
Mississippi, in Toronto, in fight everybody?

01:59:07.560 --> 01:59:12.800
Any kid that wants to come, can come to your clinics.

01:59:12.800 --> 01:59:15.680
I said I can do that.

01:59:15.680 --> 01:59:22.680
So I went down to did clinics.

01:59:22.680 --> 01:59:27.680
I actually joined myself.

01:59:27.680 --> 01:59:38.520
And Charlie says to me, you know we're not going to do anything happen to you.

01:59:38.520 --> 01:59:43.520
I said, okay.

01:59:43.520 --> 01:59:49.120
And so I had armed guards.

01:59:49.120 --> 01:59:55.640
But they were like the secret service you never knew they were around.

01:59:55.640 --> 02:00:02.640
And they gave me such.

02:00:02.640 --> 02:00:07.640
Oh, the high.

02:00:07.640 --> 02:00:12.040
1964, this is Mississippi Freedom Summer.

02:00:12.040 --> 02:00:16.240
They were in our chanee in Goodland, the first three civil rights workers on the very

02:00:16.240 --> 02:00:18.240
